      • QFTADD

        public static void QFTADD(QubitRegister qft,
                          int b)
        Changes the state of a QubitRegister from QFT(a) to QFT(a + b). The first parameter of this MUST have gone through the QFT function beforehand, and the result will only be found by performing the inverse QFT function.
        Parameters:
        qft - a QubitRegister for the function to be applied on, already passed through the QFT function
        b - value to be added to the register

      • CQFTADD

        public static void CQFTADD(QubitRegister qft,
                           int b,
                           Qubit c)
        Changes the state of a QubitRegister from QFT(a) to QFT(a + b) if the control Qubit is set. The first parameter of this MUST have gone through the QFT function beforehand, and the result will only be found by performing the inverse QFT function.
        Parameters:
        qft - a QubitRegister for the function to be applied on, already passed through the QFT function
        b - value to be added to the register
        c - the control Qubit

      • grovers

        public static int grovers(java.util.function.Consumer<QubitRegister> oracle,
                          int length)
        Performs Grovers search algorithm. Finds a particular value of an oracle function in O(sqrt(N)) evaluations
        Parameters:
        oracle - function to be searched. This oracle function should flip the polarity of whichever state is to be searched for.
        length - the amount of bits in the result to be searched
        Returns:
        the value whose phase is flipped through the oracle

      • deutschJozsa

        public static boolean deutschJozsa(java.util.function.Consumer<QubitRegister> oracle,
                                   int length)
        Determines whether a predicate function is constant or balanced. The function should flip the phase of any "true" values and leave others alone.
        Parameters:
        oracle - predicate function
        length - length of QubitRegister this function should operate on
        Returns:
        evaluates to true if constant, and false if balanced

      • oracle

        public static java.util.function.Consumer<QubitRegister> oracle(java.util.function.Predicate<java.lang.Integer> function)
        Creates a quantum function that flips the phase of any basis state coefficients as determined by the predicate specified.
        Parameters:
        function - predicate to determine which basis state coefficients are phase-flipped
        Returns:
        a quantum oracle function representation of the predicate given

      • quantumFunction

        public static java.util.function.BiConsumer<QubitRegister,QubitRegister> quantumFunction(java.util.function.UnaryOperator<java.lang.Integer> function)
        Creates a quantum function version of a given integer operator. The resulting function will take two registers as input, one to be used as input for the function, and the other to be used as a regiser for the output. Any data in the output register will be ignored. The resulant function will instantiate a gate of arbitrary size, that will execute the function given.
        Parameters:
        function - The function to be mapped into a quantum function
        Returns:
        the quantum function created

      • periodFinder

        public static QubitRegister periodFinder(java.util.function.BiConsumer<QubitRegister,QubitRegister> oracle,
                                         int inputLength,
                                         int outputLength)
        More likely to evaluate to a possible period of a quantum function.
        Parameters:
        oracle - function that takes in two registers. This function changes the value of the second to the output of a function with the first.
        inputLength - length of the input register of the function
        outputLength - length of the output register of the function
        Returns:
        a QubitRegister with higher probability to evaluate to the period of the function

      • shorsAlgorithm

        public static int shorsAlgorithm(int N)
        Performs a rudimentary, inefficient version of Shor's factorization algorithm. This will print out debug information, and will occasionally reproduce the value to be factored. Should really only be tested on the values 15 or 21, as this is unusable with square numbers.
        Parameters:
        N - value to be factored, probably should not exceed 21
        Returns:
        a factor of N

      • randomBit

        uses a Hadamard gate to create a superposition, and collapses that superposition for a random boolean value.
        Returns:
        a random boolean

      • main

        public static void main(java.lang.String[] args)
        A simple test to prove the system is in working order. Prints out the millis taken to perform the operation, should be around 100.
